        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>While CO had rarely been seen in debris disks, ALMA recently discovered CO released in planetesimal collisions around beta Pic (Dent et al. 2014), suggesting that CO is an inevitable product of a debris disk. At no extra cost to the continuum sensitivity our observations will also search for CO J=3-2. If detected this would be the first CO detection around a &gt;30Myr star (see Matra et al. 2015). The disk's Keplerian motion is 3.2-4.2km/s (at the outer-inner edges), so the 0.85km/s resolution means the line would be resolved and kinematic information would be used to constrain the disk structure (e.g., disentangling projection effects for clumpy disk structures as we did for beta Pic, Dent et al. 2014).</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The 0.7" resolution is optimal for the scales of dynamical interest in the disk. The synthesized beam of 12au clearly resolves the disk's ~70au radius inner edge, which is projected at 70deg inclination to our line-of-sight, also allowing point source clumps to be resolved in the inner regions (see Fig. 3). The beam is also large enough to detect the disk if it is as broad as allowed by the SCUBA2 observations (120au, as assumed in Fig. 3). The largest scale of interest is the outer disk radius of 120au=7". Thus the whole disk is guaranteed to fit within the ~17" primary beam and so only one pointing is necessary to image the disk.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The sensitivity requirement is based on the continuum flux. We used the OST to simulate ALMA observations for a suite of models for the potential disk morphology (see Fig. 3). All models are consistent with the previous observations (Fig. 2), but with very different implications for the outer planetary system's architecture and evolution. Changing the simulation duration showed that a sensitivity of 20uJy/beam is required to differentiate between the different models; e.g., this results in a S/N of 20 per beam, sufficient to detect the 15% brightness asymmetry in the eccentric models at S/N of 3 per beam.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
